article.headline: Cardell scores 23 points for Aggies
article.linkText: Utah State moves into Big West top spot
article.story: LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Utah State coach Stew Morrill refused to call it a pep talk. "We should play energized and we had some guys not doing that," he said. "(At) halftime that was stressed -- very vocally." The Aggies (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) must have listened to their coach, using second-half runs of 9-0 and 15-0 in a 67-47 victory over Long Beach State on Thursday night. Cardell Butler had 23 points, including nine of the Aggies' first 10 points. He made all eight of his free throws and had six rebounds. "We didn't play well in the first half and then the coach chews us out and we came out and play hard," Butler said. "But we cannot keep playing like that." At halftime, Utah State (23-2, 15-1 Big West Conference) held a six-point lead over the 49ers, but Morrill was upset with his team. "We had some guys cloudy out there in the first half. There was a lot of lolleygagging and I was not happy with it," he said. "Second half we did what we've done all year to win. We played with some energy." Kevin Roberts and Marcel Jackson each had 10 points for the 49ers (6-18, 4-11), who led for most of the game's first 8 minutes. But Mark Brown's jumper gave the Aggies a 12-10 lead and Utah State was up 29-23 at halftime. The 49ers started the second half on an 8-4 run and tied the game on Kevin Roberts' layup, but the Aggies went on a 6-0 run. Long Beach then scratched within 39-38 when Lucian Graham drained a 3-pointer, but Utah State went on the 9-0 run to lead 48-38. Reserve Mike Ahmad had six points in Utah State's 15-0 run. Reserve Ian McVey added a career-high seven points. "It's fun to see Ian be ready to go and play well," Morrill said, "and Mike Ahmad came in and played well," "I thought our guys got too tickled with themselves after hitting that 3-pointer and we lost focused on trying to defend them," Long Beach State coach Larry Reynolds said. "They have a lot of weapons and they are very methodical on what they do, and they made that nice little run." Long Beach State outrebounded Utah State 19-18 in the first half, but had 10 fewer than the 49ers in the second half. "We were aggressive on the boards in the second half," Morrill said. "Mostly this time of year you need that energy and concentration. That's a huge thing." Morrill also said, "Changing defenses kept (Long Beach) out of rhythm." The 49ers' 47 points was their third-worst scoring output of the season. The Aggies also held them to 46 points at Utah State on Jan. 31.
